remarks: This week we saw the Haystack fire exploded which reportedly started as Fire 163 that we first reported on June 7th. It seemed to smolder underground for several days, and on June 14th conditions were suitable for it to ignite above-ground foliage. Over the past several days the fire has continued to spread, moving east through mostly spruce and tracking around a deciduous stand which is characteristic of boreal systems. Flame retardant (unknown quantity) was dropped on site and bulldozers constructed fire break lines - both of which could have impacted plots. No plots were directly burned.

remarks: This week we saw the Haystack fire exploded which reportedly started as Fire 163 that we first reported on June 7th. It seemed to smolder underground for several days, and on June 14th conditions were suitable for it to ignite above-ground foliage. Over the past several days the fire has continued to spread, moving east through mostly spruce and tracking around a deciduous stand which is characteristic of boreal systems. The Haystack fire is located almost entirely within the Caribou Creek watershed. Flame retardant (unknown quantity) was dropped in the watershed at the head of Caribou Creek and bulldozers constructed fire break lines - both of which will likely impact water quality. No plots were directly burned.

dateRemarks: Start date is when the wildfire is estimated to have reached McRae Creek's downstream area.
remarks: A lightning-caused wildfire ignited on August 5, 2023, four miles NE of McKenzie Bridge, OR, was later named the Lookout Fire and resulted in substantial firefighting response. The size would reach 25,754 acres. https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident-information/orwif-lookout-fire The fire burned large areas of the forest in Lookout Creek's watershed, of which McRae Creek (MCRA) is a sub-watershed. The fire approached the McRae watershed from the south and appears to have burned the forest around the lower creek, from its confluence with Lookout Creek and reaching the study reach around August 27. However, a road (NF 325) about 200 m to the southeast of the creek, near where MCRA infrastructure is located and is the access road for the study reach, appears to have acted as a fire break. On October 10, the fire was reported to be 100% contained, with cooler weather and rain events providing fire-suppressing conditions. As of October 19, the extent and severity of impact to the study reach is unknown and the experimental forest remains closed to entry by NEON staff. The site lost power on October 20, presumably due to empty fuel, and staff is currently coordinating fuel delivery and will attempt to remotely restart the generation equipment. Published reports from the USFS Burned Area Emergency Response Team show the study reach area experienced low severity soil burn and 0-50% basal area mortality.

dateRemarks: End date is the 100% fire containment date.
remarks: A lightning-caused wildfire ignited on August 5, 2023, four miles NE of McKenzie Bridge, OR, was later named the Lookout Fire and resulted in substantial firefighting response. The size would reach 25,754 acres. https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident-information/orwif-lookout-fire The fire burned large areas of the forest in Lookout Creek's watershed, of which McRae Creek (MCRA) is a sub-watershed. The fire approached the McRae watershed from the south and appears to have burned the forest around the lower creek, from its confluence with Lookout Creek and reaching the study reach around August 27. However, a road (NF 325) within 100 m to its south, where MCRA infrastructure is located and is the access road for the study reach, appears to have acted as a fire break. On October 10, the fire was reported to be 100% contained, with cooler weather and rain events providing fire-suppressing conditions. Published reports from the USFS Burned Area Emergency Response Team show the study reach area experienced low severity soil burn and 0-50% basal area mortality.

remarks: The Bush Fire started along Highway 87 on June 13th, 2020. On June 15th, 2020, the fire spread north along the highway, and into the area of Sycamore Creek watershed above and to the east of the site. Fire is likely to impact site either directly burning the site, having fire retardant dropped on the site, or will be indirectly impacted once ash and debris moves into the site with a storm event. https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/6773/# Update as of 20200618 at 10AM local time, fire is ~115,000 acres. Fire hasn't burned the site, and a line is being maintained just west of the site along state highway 87. As of 20200701, the fire is 98% contained and is only burning within the secured perimeter of the fire. The total acreage is 193,455 acres. SYCA was not burned. Reports of water being used from nearby pond to help control fire over the past few weeks. While we have not been to the site to confirm any impact, we are assuming no areas at the site were impacted by the fire. Once staff return to site, another record will be made if impacts occurred.

The Maverick fire, an approximately 1000 acre wildfire, burned near the community of Sunflower about five miles away from SYCA reach. No area within NEON sampling boundaries was burned. Likely impacts will occur once rain runoff carries ash and debris down the watershed.

The Maverick fire, an approximately 1000 acre wildfire, burned near the community of Sunflower about five miles away from SYCA reach. No area within NEON sampling boundaries was burned. Likely impacts will occur once rain runoff carries ash and debris down the watershed.

dateRemarks: Unsure of actual date of fire. Noticed burn scar between site visits, and narrowed down date range based on information found here: https://gacc.nifc.gov/swcc
remarks: A small fire burned along Arizona State Highway 87 which runs parallel to Sycamore Creek. The fire burned less than five acres and was named the Mud Fire. The burn scar is in the uplands above the creek and outside of the NEON permitted sampling area. Ash and debris runoff will likely impact the site once it rains. The area of the NEON site that would see impacts to this runoff is near the bottom of the site where there is a small tributary that only flows during large scale thunderstorms during the Monsoon season.
